<h2 id="TwoConcLibe">1. Two Concepts of Liberty</h2>

<p>
Imagine you are driving a car through town, and you come to a fork in
the road. You turn left, but no one was forcing you to go one way or
the other. Next you come to a crossroads. You turn right, but no one
was preventing you from going left or straight on. There is no traffic
to speak of and there are no diversions or police roadblocks. So you
seem, as a driver, to be completely free. But this picture of your
situation might change quite dramatically if we consider that the
reason you went left and then right is that you&rsquo;re addicted to
cigarettes and you&rsquo;re desperate to get to the tobacco shop
before it closes. Rather than <em>driving</em>, you feel you are
<em>being driven</em>, as your urge to smoke leads you uncontrollably
to turn the wheel first to the left and then to the right. Moreover,
you&rsquo;re perfectly aware that your turning right at the crossroads
means you&rsquo;ll probably miss a train that was to take you to an
appointment you care about very much. You long to be free of this
irrational desire that is not only threatening your longevity but is
also stopping you right now from doing what you think you ought to be
doing.</p>

<p>
This story gives us two contrasting ways of thinking of liberty. On
the one hand, one can think of liberty as the absence of obstacles
external to the agent. You are free if no one is stopping you from
doing whatever you might want to do. In the above story you appear, in
this sense, to be free. On the other hand, one can think of liberty as
the presence of control on the part of the agent. To be free, you must
be self-determined, which is to say that you must be able to control
your own destiny in your own interests. In the above story you appear,
in this sense, to be unfree: you are not in control of your own
destiny, as you are failing to control a passion that you yourself
would rather be rid of and which is preventing you from realizing what
you recognize to be your true interests. One might say that while on
the first view liberty is simply about how many doors are open to the
agent, on the second view it is more about going through the right
doors for the right reasons.</p>

<p>
In a famous essay first published in 1958, Isaiah Berlin called these
two concepts of liberty negative and positive respectively (Berlin
 1969).<sup>[<a href="notes.html#note-1" id="ref-1">1</a>]</sup>
 The reason for using these labels is that in the first case liberty
seems to be a mere <em>absence</em> of something (i.e. of obstacles,
barriers, constraints or interference from others), whereas in the
second case it seems to require the <em>presence</em> of something
(i.e. of control, self-mastery, self-determination or
self-realization). In Berlin&rsquo;s words, we use the negative
concept of liberty in attempting to answer the question &lsquo;What is
the area within which the subject&mdash;a person or group of
persons&mdash;is or should be left to do or be what he is able to do
or be, without interference by other persons?&rsquo;, whereas we use
the positive concept in attempting to answer the question &lsquo;What,
or who, is the source of control or interference that can determine
someone to do, or be, this rather than that?&rsquo; (1969, pp.
121&ndash;22).</p>

<p>
It is useful to think of the difference between the two concepts in
terms of the difference between factors that are external and factors
that are internal to the agent. While theorists of negative freedom
are primarily interested in the degree to which individuals or groups
suffer interference from external bodies, theorists of positive
freedom are more attentive to the internal factors affecting the
degree to which individuals or groups act autonomously. Given this
difference, one might be tempted to think that a political philosopher
should concentrate exclusively on negative freedom, a concern with
positive freedom being more relevant to psychology or individual
morality than to political and social institutions. This, however,
would be premature, for among the most hotly debated issues in
political philosophy are the following: <em>Is</em> the positive
concept of freedom a political concept? Can individuals or groups
achieve positive freedom through political action? Is it possible for
the state to promote the positive freedom of citizens on their behalf?
And if so, is it desirable for the state to do so? The classic texts
in the history of western political thought are divided over how these
questions should be answered: theorists in the classical liberal
tradition, like Benjamin Constant, Wilhelm von Humboldt, Herbert
Spencer, and J.S. Mill, are typically classed as answering
&lsquo;no&rsquo; and therefore as defending a negative concept of
political freedom; theorists that are critical of this tradition, like
Jean-Jacques Rousseau, G.W.F. Hegel, Karl Marx and T.H. Green, are
typically classed as answering &lsquo;yes&rsquo; and as defending a
positive concept of political freedom.</p>

<p>
In its political form, positive freedom has often been thought of as
necessarily achieved through a collectivity. Perhaps the clearest case
is that of Rousseau&rsquo;s theory of freedom, according to which
individual freedom is achieved through participation in the process
whereby one&rsquo;s community exercises collective control over its
own affairs in accordance with the &lsquo;general will&rsquo;. Put in
the simplest terms, one might say that a democratic society is a free
society because it is a self-determined society, and that a member of
that society is free to the extent that he or she participates in its
democratic process. But there are also individualist applications of
the concept of positive freedom. For example, it is sometimes said
that a government should aim actively to create the conditions
necessary for individuals to be self-sufficient or to achieve
self-realization. The welfare state has sometimes been defended on
this basis, as has the idea of a universal basic income. The negative
concept of freedom, on the other hand, is most commonly assumed in
liberal defenses of the constitutional liberties typical of
liberal-democratic societies, such as freedom of movement, freedom of
religion, and freedom of speech, and in arguments against paternalist
or moralist state intervention. It is also often invoked in defenses
of the right to private property. This said, some philosophers have
contested the claim that private property necessarily enhances
negative liberty (Cohen 1995, 2006), and still others have tried to
show that negative liberty can ground a form of egalitarianism
(Steiner 1994).</p>

<p>
After Berlin, the most widely cited and best developed analyses of the
negative concept of liberty include Hayek (1960), Day (1970),
Oppenheim (1981), Miller (1983), Steiner (1994), Carter (1999), and
Kramer (2003). Among the most prominent contemporary analyses of the
positive concept of liberty are Milne (1968), Gibbs (1976), C. Taylor
(1979), Christman (1991, 2025), and Hirschmann (2003).</p>

<h2 id="ParaPosiLibe">2. The Paradox of Positive Liberty</h2>

<p>
Many liberals, including Berlin, have suggested that the positive
concept of liberty carries with it a danger of authoritarianism.
Consider the fate of a permanent and oppressed minority. Because the
members of this minority participate in a democratic process
characterized by majority rule, they might be said to be free on the
grounds that they are members of a society exercising self-control
over its own affairs. But they are oppressed, and so are surely
unfree. Moreover, it is not necessary to see a society as democratic
in order to see it as self-controlled; one might instead adopt an
organic conception of society, according to which the collectivity is
to be thought of as a living organism, and one might believe that this
organism can be in control of itself only when its various parts are
brought into line with some rational plan devised by its wise
governors (who, to extend the metaphor, might be thought of as the
organism&rsquo;s brain). In this case, even the majority might be
oppressed in the name of liberty.</p>

<p>
Such justifications of oppression in the name of liberty are no mere
products of the liberal imagination, for there are notorious
historical examples of their endorsement by authoritarian political
leaders. Berlin, himself a liberal and writing during the cold war,
was clearly moved by the way in which the apparently noble ideal of
freedom as self-mastery or self-realization had been twisted and
distorted by the totalitarian dictators of the twentieth
century&mdash;most notably those of the Soviet Union&mdash;so as to
claim that they, rather than the liberal West, were the true champions
of freedom. The slippery slope towards this paradoxical conclusion
begins, according to Berlin, with the idea of a divided self. To
illustrate: the smoker in our story provides a clear example of a
divided self, for she is both a self that desires to get to an
appointment and a self that desires to get to the tobacconists, and
these two desires are in conflict. We can now enrich this story in a
plausible way by adding that one of these selves&mdash;the keeper of
appointments&mdash;is superior to the other: the self that is a keeper
of appointments is thus a &lsquo;higher&rsquo; self, and the self that
is a smoker is a &lsquo;lower&rsquo; self. The higher self is the
rational, reflecting self, the self that is capable of moral action
and of taking responsibility for what she does. This is the true self,
for rational reflection and moral responsibility are the features of
humans that mark them off from other animals. The lower self, on the
other hand, is the self of the passions, of unreflecting desires and
irrational impulses. One is free, then, when one&rsquo;s higher,
rational self is in control and one is not a slave to one&rsquo;s
passions or to one&rsquo;s merely empirical self. The next step down
the slippery slope consists in pointing out that some individuals are
more rational than others, and can therefore know best what is in
their and others&rsquo; rational interests. This allows them to say
that by forcing people less rational than themselves to do the
rational thing and thus to realize their true selves, they are in fact
liberating them from their merely empirical desires. Occasionally,
Berlin says, the defender of positive freedom will take an additional
step that consists in conceiving of the self as wider than the
individual and as represented by an organic social
whole&mdash;&lsquo;a tribe, a race, a church, a state, the great
society of the living and the dead and the yet unborn&rsquo;. The true
interests of the individual are to be identified with the interests of
this whole, and individuals can and should be coerced into fulfilling
these interests, for they would not resist such overall plans for
society if they were as rational and wise as the authors of those
plans. &lsquo;Once I take this view&rsquo;, Berlin says, &lsquo;I am
in a position to ignore the actual wishes of men or societies, to
bully, oppress, torture in the name, and on behalf, of their
&lsquo;real&rsquo; selves, in the secure knowledge that whatever is
the true goal of man ... must be identical with his freedom&rsquo;
(Berlin 1969, pp. 132&ndash;33).</p>

<p>
Those in the negative camp try to cut off this line of reasoning at
the first step, by denying that there is any necessary relation
between one&rsquo;s freedom and one&rsquo;s desires. Since one is free
to the extent that one is externally unprevented from doing things,
they say, one can be free to do what one does not desire to do. If
being free meant being unprevented from realizing one&rsquo;s desires,
then one could, again paradoxically, reduce one&rsquo;s unfreedom by
coming to desire fewer of the things one is unfree to do. One could
become free simply by contenting oneself with one&rsquo;s situation. A
perfectly contented slave is perfectly free to realize all of her
desires. Nevertheless, we tend to think of slavery as the opposite of
freedom. More generally, freedom is not to be confused with happiness,
for in logical terms there is nothing to stop a free person from being
unhappy or an unfree person from being happy. The happy person might
<em>feel</em> free, but whether they <em>are</em> free is another
matter (Day 1970). Proponents of the negative concept therefore tend
to avoid saying that having freedom means being unprevented from doing
as one desires. Instead, they say, it means being unprevented from
doing whatever one <em>might</em> desire to do (Steiner 1994. Cf. Van
Parijs 1995; Sugden 2006).</p>

<p>
Theorists of positive freedom might choose to bite the bullet and say
that one can indeed become more free by desiring less (see e.g.
Macmurray 1991, p.6), thus implying that the contented slave is free
after
 all.<sup>[<a href="notes.html#note-2" id="ref-2">2</a>]</sup>
 To achieve freedom, they might say, the individual must learn, not so
much to dominate certain merely empirical desires, as to rid herself
of them. As Berlin puts it, if I have a wounded leg &lsquo;there are
two methods of freeing myself from pain. One is to heal the wound. But
if the cure is too difficult or uncertain, there is another method. I
can get rid of the wound by cutting off my leg&rsquo; (1969, pp.
135&ndash;36). Taken to its extreme, this strategy of liberation
involves extinguishing as many of one&rsquo;s own desires as possible.
It is the strategy adopted by ascetics, stoics and Buddhist sages, and
involves a &lsquo;retreat into an inner citadel&rsquo;&mdash;a soul or
a purely noumenal self&mdash;in which the individual is immune to any
outside forces. But this state, even if it can be achieved, is not one
that liberals would want to call one of freedom, for it again risks
masking important forms of oppression. After all, it is often in
coming to terms with excessive external limitations in society that
individuals retreat into themselves, pretending to themselves that
they do not really desire the worldly goods or pleasures they have
been denied. Moreover, the removal of desires may also be an effect of
outside forces, such as brainwashing, which we should hardly want to
call a realization of freedom.</p>

<p>
Because the concept of negative freedom concentrates on the external
sphere in which individuals interact, it seems to provide a better
guarantee against the dangers of paternalism and authoritarianism
perceived by Berlin. To promote negative freedom is to promote the
existence of a sphere of action within which the individual is
sovereign, and within which she can pursue her own projects subject
only to the constraint that she respect the spheres of others.
Humboldt and Mill, both advocates of negative freedom, compared the
development of an individual to that of a plant: individuals, like
plants, must be allowed to grow, in the sense of developing their own
faculties to the full and according to their own inner logic. Personal
growth is something that cannot be imposed from without, but must come
from within the individual.</p>

<h2 id="RescPosiLibe">3. Rescuing Positive Liberty</h2>

<p>
Much of the more recent work on positive liberty has been motivated by
a dissatisfaction with the ideal of negative liberty combined with an
awareness of the abuses to which the positive concept is vulnerable,
as argued by Berlin. Consider the ideal defended by Humboldt and Mill,
mentioned at the end of the previous section. This ideal, it might be
argued, looks more like a positive concept of liberty than a negative
one, for positive liberty consists in exactly this growth of the
individual: the free individual is one that develops, determines and
changes her own desires and interests autonomously and from within.
This is not liberty as the mere absence of obstacles, but liberty as
autonomy or self-realization. Moreover, the promotion of this kind of
individual development does not necessarily license the authoritarian
or paternalistic outcomes feared by Berlin.</p>

<p>
Along these lines, John Christman (1991, 2005, 2009, 2013, 2025) has
argued that positive liberty concerns the <em>ways</em> in which
desires are formed&mdash;whether as a result of rational reflection on
all the options available, or as a result of pressure, manipulation or
ignorance. What it does not regard, he says, is the <em>content</em>
of an individual&rsquo;s desires. The promotion of positive freedom
need not therefore involve the claim that there is only one right
answer to the question of how a person should live, nor need it allow,
or even be compatible with, a society&rsquo;s forcing its members into
given patterns of behavior. Take the example of a Muslim woman who
claims to espouse the fundamentalist doctrines generally followed by
her family and the community in which she lives. On Christman&rsquo;s
account, this person is positively unfree if her desire to conform was
somehow oppressively imposed upon her through indoctrination,
manipulation or deceit. She is positively free, on the other hand, if
she arrived at her desire to conform while aware of other reasonable
options, if those options were genuinely available to her, and if she
weighed and assessed them rationally. Even if this woman seems to
prefer subservient behavior, there is nothing necessarily
freedom-enhancing or freedom-restricting about her having the desires
she has, since freedom regards not the content of these desires but
their mode of formation. On this view, forcing her to do certain
things rather than others can never make her more free, and
Berlin&rsquo;s paradox of positive freedom would seem to have been
avoided.</p>

<p>
This more procedural account of positive liberty allows us to point to
kinds of internal constraint that seem to fall off the radar if we
adopt only the negative concept. For example, some radical political
theorists believe it can help us to make sense of forms of oppression
and structural injustice that cannot be traced to overt acts of
prevention or coercion. On the one hand, in agreement with Berlin, we
should recognize the dangers that come with promoting the values or
interests of a person&rsquo;s &lsquo;true self&rsquo; in opposition to
what they manifestly desire. Thus, the procedural account avoids all
reference to a true self. On the other, we should recognize that
people&rsquo;s <em>actual</em> selves are inevitably formed in a
social context and that their values and senses of identity (for
example, in terms of gender or race or nationality) are shaped by
cultural influences. In this sense, the self is socially constructed,
and the social construction can itself occur in oppressive ways. The
challenge, then, is to show how a person&rsquo;s values can be thus
shaped but without the kind of oppressive imposition or manipulation
that comes not only from political coercion but also, more subtly,
from practices or institutions that stigmatize or marginalize certain
identities or that attach costs to the endorsement of values deviating
from acceptable norms, for these kinds of imposition or manipulation
can be just another way of promoting a substantive ideal of the self.
And this was exactly the danger against which Berlin was warning,
except that the danger is less visible and can be created
unintentionally (Christman 2013, 2022; Hirschmann 2003, 2013; Coole
2013).</p>

<p>
While this theory of positive freedom undoubtedly provides a tool for
criticizing the limiting effects of certain practices and institutions
in contemporary liberal societies, it remains to be seen what kinds of
political action can be pursued in order to promote content-neutral
positive liberty without encroaching on any individual&rsquo;s
rightful sphere of negative liberty. Thus, the potential conflict
between the two ideals of negative and positive freedom might survive
Christman&rsquo;s alternative analysis, albeit in a milder form. Even
if we rule out coercing individuals into specific patterns of
behavior, a state interested in promoting content-neutral positive
liberty might still have considerable space for intervention aimed at
public enlightenment, perhaps subsidizing some kinds of activities (in
order to encourage a plurality of genuine options) and financing such
intervention through taxation. Liberals might criticize this kind of
intervention on anti-paternalist grounds, objecting that such measures
will require the state to use resources in ways that the supposedly
heteronomous individuals, if left to themselves, might have chosen to
spend in other ways. In other words, even in its content-neutral form,
the ideal of positive freedom might still conflict with the liberal
idea of respect for persons, one interpretation of which involves
viewing individuals from the outside and taking their choices at face
value. From a liberal point of view, the blindness to internal
constraints can be intentional (Carter 2011a). Some liberals will make
an exception to this restriction on state intervention in the case of
the education of children, in such a way as to provide for the active
cultivation of open minds and rational reflection (see e.g., Clayton
2006). Even here, however, other liberals will object that the right
to negative liberty includes the right to decide how one&rsquo;s
children should be educated (see e.g. Galston 2002, and for
counterarguments, Clayton 2006, ch 3).</p>

<p>
Is it necessary to refer to internal constraints in order to make
sense of the phenomena of oppression and structural injustice? Some
might contest this view, or say that it is true only up to a point,
for there are at least two reasons for thinking that the oppressed are
lacking in <em>negative</em> liberty. First, while Berlin himself
equated economic and social disadvantages with natural disabilities,
claiming that neither represented constraints on negative liberty but
only on personal abilities, many theorists of negative liberty
disagree: if I lack the money to buy a jacket from a clothes shop,
then any attempt on my part to carry away the jacket is likely to meet
with preventive actions or punishment on the part of the shop keeper
or the agents of the state. This is a case of interpersonal
interference, not merely of personal inability. In the normal
circumstances of a market economy, purchasing power is indeed a very
reliable indicator of how far other people will stop you from doing
certain things if you try. It is therefore strongly correlated with
degrees of negative freedom (Cohen 1995, 2011; Waldron 1993; Carter
2007; Grant 2013). Thus, while the promotion of content-neutral
positive liberty might imply the transfer of certain kinds of
resources to members of disadvantaged groups, the same might be true
of the promotion of negative liberty. Second, negative unfreedom can
be a condition of disadvantaged groups as well as of their individual
members. Some social structures may be such as to tolerate the
liberation of only a limited number of members of a given group. G.A.
Cohen famously focused on the case of proletarians who can escape
their condition by successfully setting up a business of their own
through a mixture of hard work and luck. In such cases, while each
individual member of the disadvantaged group might be negatively free
in the sense of being unprevented from choosing this path of
liberation from their proletarian condition, the freedom of each
individual is conditional on the unfreedom of the majority of the rest
of the group, since not all can escape in this way. Each individual
member of the class therefore partakes in a form of collective
negative unfreedom (Cohen 1988, 2006; for discussion see Mason 1996;
Hindriks 2008; Grant 2013; Schmidt 2023).</p>

<h2 id="NRepLibeThirWay">4. Republican Liberty: A Third Way?</h2>

<p>
Some philosophers have rejected both the negative and the positive
ideals of freedom, claiming that liberty is not merely the enjoyment
of a sphere of non-interference but the enjoyment of certain
conditions in which such non-interference is guaranteed. These
conditions may include a democratic constitution and a series of
safeguards against a government wielding power arbitrarily, such as
popular control and the separation of powers. As Berlin points out,
there is no conceptually necessary connection between negative liberty
and any particular form of government (see also Hayek 1960). Yet it
may seem counterintuitive to say that I can in theory be free to a
significant degree while living under a dictatorship, or that a slave
can enjoy considerable liberty as long as the slave-owner is
benevolent. Would my subjection to the arbitrary power of a dictator
or slave-owner not be sufficient <em>in itself</em> to qualify me as
unfree? If it would be, then the enjoyment of freedom must require the
presence of institutions that secure each citizen&rsquo;s independence
from such arbitrary power. This kind of freedom is commonly referred
to as &lsquo;republican&rsquo;, and its foremost proponent is Philip
Pettit (1997, 2001, 2014; see also Skinner 1998, 2002; Weinstock and
Nadeau 2004; Laborde and Maynor 2008; Lovett 2010, 2022; Breen and
McBride 2015; List and Valentini 2016).</p>

<p>
Republican freedom can be understood as a kind of <em>status</em>: to
be a free person is to enjoy the rights and privileges attached to the
status of republican citizenship, whereas the paradigm of unfreedom is
having the status of slave. Even if the slave enjoys non-interference,
she is, as Pettit puts it, &lsquo;dominated&rsquo;, because she is
subject to the arbitrary power of her owner, even if that power is
never in fact exercised. Republicans therefore define freedom as
&lsquo;non-domination&rsquo;. Non-domination is distinct from negative
freedom, Pettit says, for two reasons. First, one can enjoy
non-interference without enjoying non-domination, as shown by the
above example of the slave with a non-interfering master. Second, one
can enjoy non-domination while nevertheless being interfered with,
provided that such interference is constrained to track one&rsquo;s
avowed interests thanks to republican power structures: only
<em>arbitrary</em> power is inimical to freedom, not power as such.
Republican freedom is also distinct from positive freedom as expounded
and criticized by Berlin. First, republican freedom does not consist
in the activity of virtuous political participation, although such
participation is seen as instrumentally related to freedom as
non-domination. Second, republican freedom cannot lead to anything
like the oppressive consequences Berlin associated with positive
liberty, because it has a commitment to non-domination and to
liberal-democratic institutions already built into it. This last point
also makes it quite different from Christman&rsquo;s concept of
positive freedom. Christman argues for the compatibility of positive
freedom with liberalism, but not by pointing to a conceptual link
between freedom and liberal-democratic institutions.</p>

<p>
Much of the appeal of freedom as non-domination lies in its apparent
ability to capture phenomena such as oppression and structural
injustice without appealing to internal constraints. It has been
applied not only to relations of domination between governments and
citizens, but also to relations of domination between employers and
workers (Breen and McBride 2015), between husbands and wives (Lovett
2022), and between able-bodied and disabled people (De Wispelaere and
Casassas 2014; S&eacute;pulchre 2022).</p>

<p>
It remains to be seen, however, whether republican freedom is
ultimately distinguishable from negative freedom, or whether
republicans have instead simply provided good arguments to the effect
that negative freedom is best promoted, <em>on balance and over
time</em>, through certain kinds of political institutions rather than
others. While there is no conceptually necessary connection between
negative liberty and democratic government, there may nevertheless be
a strong empirical correlation between the two. Many theorists have
argued that republican policies are therefore best defended
empirically on the basis of negative freedom, rather than by rejecting
that concept (Carter 1999, 2008; Kramer 2003, 2008, Goodin and Jackson
2007; Moen 2024). An important premise in such an argument is that the
extent of a person&rsquo;s negative freedom is a function not simply
of how many single actions are prevented, but of how many different
<em>act-combinations</em> are prevented. People who can achieve their
goals only by bowing and scraping to their masters must be seen as
less free, negatively, than people who can achieve those goals
unconditionally. Another important premise is that the extent to which
people are negatively free depends, in part, on the
<em>probability</em> with which they would be constrained from
performing future acts or act-combinations should they attempt to do
so. People who are subject to arbitrary power are less free in the
<em>negative</em> sense, even if they do not <em>actually</em> suffer
interference, because the probability of their suffering constraints
is always greater (<em>ceteris paribus</em>, as a matter of empirical
fact) than it would be if they were not subject to that arbitrary
power. Only this greater probability, these liberal theorists say, can
adequately explain the concerns expressed by republicans about the
<em>fear</em>, the <em>sense of exposure</em>, and the
<em>precariousness</em> of the dominated (see Bruin 2009; Lang 2012;
Shnayderman 2012; Kirby 2016; Carter and Shnayderman 2019).</p>

<p>
In reply, republicans have insisted that freedom as non-domination is
distinct from negative liberty because what matters for an
agent&rsquo;s freedom is not the <em>improbability</em> but the
<em>impossibility</em> of others interfering. For example, a husband
might be kind and generous, and therefore be <em>extremely
unlikely</em> ever to deny his wife the same opportunities as he
himself enjoys; but the wife is still <em>dominated</em> if the
structure of norms in her society is such as to permit husbands to
frustrate the choices of their wives in numerous ways. If she lives in
such a society, she is still <em>subject to</em> the husband&rsquo;s
power whether he likes it or not. Moreover, the wife&rsquo;s
subjection to his power will tend to influence how third parties treat
her &ndash; for example, in terms of offering employment
opportunities.</p>

<p>
Taken at face value, however, the requirement of impossibility of
interference seems over-demanding, as it is never completely
impossible for others to constrain me. For example, it is not
impossible that I be stabbed by someone as I walk down the street this
afternoon. If the <em>mere possibility</em> of the stabbing makes me
unfree to walk down the street, then unfreedom is everywhere and the
achievement of freedom is impossible. To avoid this worry, republicans
have qualified their impossibility requirement: for me to be free to
walk down the street, it must be impossible for others to stab me
<em>with impunity</em> (Pettit 2008a, 2008b; Skinner 2008). But this
qualification is open to objections. Is impunity a purely formal
requirement, or should we say that no one can carry out a street
stabbing with impunity if, say, at least 70% of such stabbings lead to
prosecution? Even if 100% of such stabbings lead to prosecution, there
will still be some stabbings. Will they not be sources of unfreedom
for the victims?</p>

<p>
Another problem with the requirement of impossibility is that there
will always be some <em>group</em> of individuals who, if they
coordinated, could interfere arbitrarily with me. Such coalitions are
<em>possible</em>, even if <em>unlikely</em>. Since no one is powerful
enough to resist the interference of <em>all</em> such possible
coalitions, not only the weak but also the powerful turn out to be
dominated by others who might act in concert. Domination is thus
pervasive, and republican freedom impossible to achieve (Dowding 2011;
Simpson 2017). To avoid this conclusion, republicans have argued that
not all potential coalitions possess dominating power. Consider two
would-be muggers who might wish to coordinate an attack on me. They
form a potential team but, it might be said, they do not dominate me
unless they share an awareness of one another&rsquo;s intentions and
have a salient strategy for acting together. When such epistemic
conditions are met, they constitute a capable team, and only capable
teams dominate. Non-domination, while demanding, is therefore
achievable (Lovett and Pettit 2018). Yet this reply has something of
an <em>ad hoc</em> feel. Moreover, it does not conclusively resolve
the problem, since sufficiently large or suitably situated groups will
still qualify as capable teams. Too many agents seem to retain the
capacity to form dominating coalitions (Simpson 2019).</p>

<p>
A more recent republican response to the impossibility problem invokes
the concept of &lsquo;ignorability&rsquo; (Ingham and Lovett 2019).
The idea is that each potentially interfering agent has an actual
type, consisting in her actual preferences regarding whether to
interfere, and a range of possible types corresponding to preferences
she might have in other possible worlds. There are some possible
interfering types that can be ignored and therefore need not be
considered sources of domination. They can be ignored when the common
knowledge of a discrepancy between the actual type and the possible
interfering types does not have significant practical consequences. To
illustrate: in a traditional patriarchal society where husbands are
generally expected or permitted to relate to their wives in coercive
or exploitative ways, the news that a particular husband is benevolent
will have significant practical consequences: third parties will treat
his wife as more autonomous and, say, offer her employment. His
possible interfering types are therefore not ignorable, and she is
dominated. By contrast, in a liberal society like San Francisco, where
husbands are generally expected to be non-interfering, the same news
changes nothing significant in anyone&rsquo;s behavior. His possible
interfering types are therefore ignorable, and his wife is free.
Hence, a possible interfering type is ignorable if and only if its
becoming common knowledge that the agent&rsquo;s actual type does not
belong to that set of possible interfering types would have no
significant practical consequences. By narrowing the range of possible
worlds that freedom pertains to, the notion of ignorability is
intended to make room for the possibility of republican freedom.</p>

<p>
Negative liberty theorists have raised two main objections to this
move (Jafarov and Huseynli 2022). The first is that the criterion of
ignorability is reducible to a threshold of sufficiently low
probability. To say that the absence of certain interfering types
would have &lsquo;no significant practical consequences&rsquo; is, in
effect, to say that interference is already unlikely enough to be
disregarded by rational agents. Ignorability therefore collapses into
the probabilistic standard that republicans sought to reject. The
second objection challenges the claim that ignorability entails
non-domination (assuming the republican account of domination). There
are cases in which an agent&rsquo;s possible interfering types are
ignorable, yet domination persists because the agent retains an
insufficiently constrained capacity to interfere. For example, suppose
a husband has an unconstrained ability to prevent his wife from
leaving the home, but she is terminally ill and in a deep depression
and has no desire to leave, and everyone in society is aware of this
fact. Since nobody&rsquo;s behavior would change upon learning that
the husband is not the type to exercise his power, his possible
interfering types are ignorable. Yet she is dominated, since he
retains an unconstrained ability to frustrate her choices. The
possibility of domination with ignorability suggests that the notion
of ignorability excludes cases that republicans ought, out of
consistency, to count as unfreedom (for a response, see Lovett and
Ingham 2022; and for further discussion, see Inoue 2025; Moen
2025).</p>

<p>
The jury is still out on whether republicans have successfully carved
out a third concept of freedom that is distinct from those of negative
and positive liberty. This conceptual uncertainty need not itself cast
doubt on the distinctness and attractiveness of republicanism as a set
of political prescriptions. Rather, what it leaves open is the
question of the ultimate normative bases of those prescriptions: is
non-domination something that supervenes on certain configurations of
negative freedom and unfreedom, and therefore explainable in terms of
such configurations, or is it something truly distinct from those
configurations?</p>

<h2 id="OneConcLibeFreeTriaRela">5. One Concept of Liberty: Freedom as a Triadic Relation</h2>

<p>
The two sides identified by Berlin disagree over which of two
different concepts best captures the political ideal of liberty. Does
this fact not denote the presence of some more basic
<em>agreement</em> between the two sides? How, after all, could they
see their disagreement as one about the nature of liberty if they did
not think of themselves as in some sense <em>talking about the same
thing</em>? In an influential article, the American legal philosopher
Gerald MacCallum (1967) put forward the following answer: there is in
fact only <em>one</em> basic concept of freedom, on which both sides
in the debate <em>converge</em>. What the so-called negative and
positive theorists disagree about is how this single concept of
freedom should be interpreted. Indeed, in MacCallum&rsquo;s view,
there are a great many different possible interpretations of freedom,
and it is only Berlin&rsquo;s artificial dichotomy that has led us to
think in terms of there being two.</p>

<p>
MacCallum defines the basic concept of freedom&mdash;the concept on
which everyone agrees&mdash;as follows: a subject, or agent, is free
from certain constraints, or preventing conditions, to do or become
certain things. Freedom is therefore a <em>triadic
relation</em>&mdash;that is, a relation between <em>three things</em>:
an agent, certain preventing conditions, and certain doings or
becomings of the agent. Any statement about freedom or unfreedom can
be translated into a statement of the above form by specifying
<em>what</em> is free or unfree, <em>from</em> what it is free or
unfree, and what it is free or unfree <em>to do or become</em>. Any
claim about the presence or absence of freedom in a given situation
will therefore make certain assumptions about what counts as an agent,
what counts as a constraint or limitation on freedom, and what counts
as a purpose that the agent can be described as either free or unfree
to carry out.</p>

<p>
The definition of freedom as a triadic relation was first put forward
in the seminal work of Felix Oppenheim in the 1950s and
<!--StartFragment -->&rsquo;<!--EndFragment -->60s. Oppenheim saw that
an important meaning of &lsquo;freedom&rsquo; in the context of
political and social philosophy was as a relation between two agents
and a particular (impeded or unimpeded) action. However,
Oppenheim&rsquo;s interpretation of freedom was an example of what
Berlin would call a negative concept. What MacCallum did was to
generalize this triadic structure so that it would cover all possible
claims about freedom, whether of the negative or the positive variety.
In MacCallum&rsquo;s framework, unlike in Oppenheim&rsquo;s, the
interpretation of each of the three variables is left open. In other
words, MacCallum&rsquo;s position is a <em>meta-theoretical</em> one:
his is a theory about the differences between theorists of
freedom.</p>

<p>
To illustrate MacCallum&rsquo;s point, let us return to the example of
the smoker driving to the tobacco shop. In describing this person as
either free or unfree, we make assumptions about each of
MacCallum&rsquo;s three variables. If we say that the driver is
<em>free</em>, what we probably mean is that an agent, consisting in
the driver&rsquo;s empirical self, is free from external (physical or
legal) obstacles to do whatever he or she might want to do. If, on the
other hand, we say that the driver is <em>unfree</em>, what we
probably mean is that an agent, consisting in a higher or rational
self, is made unfree by internal, psychological constraints to carry
out some rational, authentic or virtuous plan. Notice that in both
claims there is a negative element and a positive element: each claim
about freedom assumes <em>both</em> that freedom is <em>freedom
from</em> something (i.e., preventing conditions) <em>and</em> that it
is <em>freedom to</em> do or become something. The dichotomy between
<em>freedom from</em> and <em>freedom to</em> is therefore a false
one, and it is misleading to say that those who see the driver as free
employ a negative concept and those who see the driver as unfree
employ a positive one. What these two camps differ over is the way in
which one should interpret each of the three variables in the triadic
freedom-relation. More precisely, what they differ over is the
<em>extension</em> to be assigned to each of the variables.</p>

<p>
Thus, those whom Berlin places in the negative camp typically conceive
of the agent as having the same extension as that which it is
generally given in ordinary discourse: they tend to think of the agent
as an individual human being and as including all of the empirical
beliefs and desires of that individual. Those in the so-called
positive camp, on the other hand, often depart from the ordinary
notion, in one sense imagining the agent as more extensive than in the
ordinary notion, and in another sense imagining it as less extensive:
they think of the agent as having a greater extension than in ordinary
discourse in cases where they identify the agent&rsquo;s true desires
and aims with those of some collectivity of which she is a member; and
they think of the agent as having a lesser extension than in ordinary
discourse in cases where they identify the true agent with only a
subset of her empirical beliefs and desires&mdash;i.e., with those
that are rational, authentic or virtuous. Secondly, those in
Berlin&rsquo;s positive camp tend to take a wider view of what counts
as a constraint on freedom than those in his negative camp: the set of
relevant obstacles is more extensive for the former than for the
latter, since negative theorists tend to count only external obstacles
as constraints on freedom, whereas positive theorists also allow that
one may be constrained by internal factors, such as irrational
desires, fears or ignorance. And thirdly, those in Berlin&rsquo;s
positive camp tend to take a narrower view of what counts as a purpose
one can be free to fulfill. The set of relevant purposes is less
extensive for them than for the negative theorists, for we have seen
that they tend to restrict the relevant set of actions or states to
those that are rational, authentic or virtuous, whereas those in the
negative camp tend to extend this variable so as to cover any action
or state the agent might desire.</p>

<p>
On MacCallum&rsquo;s analysis, then, there is no simple dichotomy
between positive and negative liberty; rather, we should recognize
that there is a whole range of possible interpretations or
<em>conceptions</em> of the single concept of liberty. (The
distinction between a concept and its various conceptions comes from
Rawls 1971, p.5. A number of authors have applied it to the concept of
liberty, explicating that concept by means of MacCallum&rsquo;s
triadic formula&mdash;see e.g. Gray 1991.)</p>

<h2 id="AnalCons">6. The Analysis of Constraints</h2>

<p>
To illustrate the range of conceptions of the concept of liberty made
available by MacCallum&rsquo;s analysis, let us now take a closer look
at his second variable&mdash;that of constraints. These can be
classified along two logically independent dimensions: their
<em>sources</em> and their <em>types.</em> By constraint-source we
mean the factors that bring about a constraint: must an obstacle be
attributable to the conduct of other persons in order to count as a
constraint on freedom, or can purely natural events and self-inflicted
incapacities also render one unfree? By constraint-types we mean
classes of constraints identified in terms of their intrinsic
properties: are constraints on freedom limited to physical barriers
such as walls or locked doors, or can they include mental barriers
such as phobias?; and does a constraint on freedom necessarily render
an action impossible, or does it suffice that it make the action more
difficult or costly?</p>

<h3 id="SourCons">6.1 Sources of Constraint</h3>

<p>
Most proponents of negative conceptions&mdash;including, as we have
seen, Berlin&mdash;hold that freedom is essentially a <em>social
relation</em>. They therefore limit the range of obstacles that count
as constraints on freedom to those attributable to the conduct of
other agents. If I am incapacitated by natural causes&mdash;by a
genetic handicap, say, or by being struck by lightning&mdash;I may be
rendered <em>unable</em> to do certain things, but I am not, for that
reason, rendered <em>unfree</em> to do them. This observation yields a
distinction between <em>unfreedoms</em>, understood as inabilities due
to the conduct of other persons, and <em>mere inabilities</em>, which
are due to nature or to oneself. If you lock me in my house, I am both
unable and unfree to leave. But if I am unable to leave because of a
naturally caused illness or a snow drift which has blocked the door
from the outside, or because I locked the door from the inside and
destroyed the key, I am not unfree to leave.</p>

<p>
There are different ways of cashing out the idea that the source of
unfreedom is the conduct of other persons. One possibility is the
<em>causal</em> view, according to which I am unfree to do something
whenever my inability is causally attributable to another
person&rsquo;s action (Oppenheim 1961, 1985; Steiner 1994; Kramer
2003). Another possibility is the <em>moral responsibility</em> view,
according to which we must ask whether the agent who created the
obstacle can be held morally responsible for my inability
(Kristj&aacute;nsson 1996; Miller 1983; Shnayderman 2013; Schmidt
2016). The latter view makes freedom partly dependent on moral
judgments, whereas the former treats freedom as an empirical
behavioural concept, requiring only knowledge of causal relations, and
therefore allows persons with different moral judgements to agree on
whether someone is unfree. It has recently been suggested that if
moral responsibility is understood broadly, as <em>moral
answerability</em>, the two views may converge, since the set of
actions for which agents are answerable is arguably coextensive with
the set of actions that generate unfreedom under the causality view.
On this capacious account, agents can, in principle, be asked to
answer for any obstacle their actions causally bring about, where
answerability does not entail any specific moral response such as
blame or praise (Huseynli 2026).</p>

<p>
The relevant conduct of other agents might be said to include only
actions, or both actions and omissions. Suppose I am unable to leave
my house because a snow drift has blocked the door, but you, being
outside, could easily remove the snow. If you fail to do so, does your
omission render me unfree? Some theorists answer that it does not
render me unfree (Oppenheim 1985; Steiner 1994; Kramer 2003;
Shnayderman 2013). Others argue that certain omissions, especially
those for which agents can be held responsible, or those involving a
failure to intervene where obstacles are easily removable, do count as
sources of unfreedom (Kristj&aacute;nsson 1996; Miller 1985; Christman
2025).</p>

<p>
Among those who agree that only the conduct of others generates
<em>un</em>freedom, there is further disagreement about what we might
call the conditions of <em>freedom</em>. If I suffer from a natural or
self-inflicted inability to do something, I am <em>not unfree</em> to
do it, if unfreedom is understood as a social relation. But should we
say that I therefore remain <em>free</em> to do it? Or should we
instead say that the inability entails my lack of freedom to do it
without entailing my <em>un</em>freedom to do it? The former position
implies a &lsquo;bivalent&rsquo; conception of freedom, according to
which a person is necessarily either free or unfree to do something
(Steiner 2001; Carter and Steiner 2022). The latter position implies a
&lsquo;trivalent&rsquo; conception, according to which there are some
things that a person is neither free nor unfree to do. Kramer (2003)
endorses a trivalent conception whereby freedom is identified with
ability, and unfreedom with the prevention by others of outcomes that
the agent would otherwise be able to bring about. The unfreedom to do
<em>x</em> is a social relation; the freedom to do <em>x</em> is
not.</p>

<p>
Some theorists go even further, arguing that we should not only
identify freedom with ability, but we should also identify unfreedom
with inability, thereby denying any distinction between unfreedoms and
mere inabilities (Crocker 1980; Cohen 2011, pp. 193&ndash;97; Sen
1992; Van Parijs 1995; Garnett 2022a; Rainbolt 2024). The main
motivation for this <em>bivalent ability-based</em> conception of
freedom is that the distinction between unfreedom and mere inability
lacks a principled justification and may reflect ideological bias,
implying that mere inabilities are somehow less important than social
unfreedoms. Bivalent freedom-as-ability is sometimes referred to as a
kind of positive freedom&mdash;somewhat confusingly, given that it is
very different from what Berlin meant by positive freedom. It is
generally assumed in defenses of the so-called capability approach to
justice and human development (Sen 1985, 1988, 1992; Nussbaum, 2006,
2011).</p>

<p>
The question of sources has important implications for how we assess
economic constraints like recession, poverty and unemployment. Do such
conditions merely render people unable to act, or do they also render
them unfree? Libertarians and egalitarians have often provided
contrasting answers to this question by appealing to different
conceptions of the sources of constraints. One way of denying that
such economic constraints produce unfreedom is to adopt an even more
restrictive view of its sources, counting only those obstacles that
are <em>intentionally</em> brought about by other persons. In this
case, impersonal economic forces, being brought about unintentionally,
can restrict people&rsquo;s options without making them any less free.
This view has been adopted by several market-oriented libertarians,
including, most famously, Friedrich von Hayek (1960, 1982), according
to whom freedom is the absence of coercion, understood as subjection
to the arbitrary will of another. (Notice the somewhat surprising
similarity between this conception of freedom and the republican
conception discussed earlier, in section 4). This narrow conception of
a constraint is contested not only by those adopting the notion of
freedom as ability, but also by those adopting a broader conception of
the sources of social unfreedom. Notice, moreover, that economic
hardship can be understood as creating unfreedom on both the causal
view and the moral responsibility view of social freedom (see Cohen
2011 cited at the end of section 3).</p>

<p>
But why would one want to distinguish, in the first place, between
unfreedom and mere inability? The mere claim that freedom is a social
relation looks more like a stipulation than a justification. An answer
might be found by examining more closely our ideas about the
<em>value</em> of freedom. Freedom might be said to have
&lsquo;ability-independent&rsquo; value: even when we are unable to
act, the fact that our inability is not due to the conduct of others
can itself be something that matters morally (Morriss 2012; Intropi
2022; Huseynli 2025). One reason for thinking this might be that
abstaining from constraining others is part of what respectful conduct
amounts to. It would explain why individuals may object to limits
imposed by the law or the conduct of other individuals even where they
already lacked the relevant abilities. The idea of freedom&rsquo;s
ability-independent value supports the idea that debates about freedom
cannot be reduced to those about ability or capability, since the
normative significance of social freedom extends beyond what persons
can do and become, to how they stand <em>in relation to
others</em>.</p>

<h3 id="DistConsSourConsType">6.2 Distinguishing Constraint Sources and Constraint Types</h3>

<p>
Constraint types and constraint sources are often not distinguished
carefully. For example, those who interpret freedom as a social
relation are often said to count only those obstacles that are
external to the agent. But the term &lsquo;external&rsquo; is
ambiguous in this context, for it might refer either to the location
of the obstacle itself, or to the location of its source (this
ambiguity was present in the brief summary in section 1). Obstacles
that count as internal in terms of their location include
psychological phenomena such as ignorance, irrational desires,
illusions and phobias. Such obstacles can arise in various ways: for
example, they might have a genetic origin, or they might be brought
about intentionally by others, as in the case of brainwashing or
manipulation. In the first case we have an internal constraint brought
about by features of the agent herself, and in this sense
<em>internally</em>; in the second, an internal constraint
intentionally imposed by another agent, and in this sense
<em>externally</em>. The two dimensions of type and source are
therefore logically independent: it is theoretically possible to
combine a narrow view of what counts as a source of a constraint with
a broad view of what types of obstacle count as unfreedom-generating
constraints, or <em>vice versa</em>. As a result, it is not clear that
theorists who are normally placed in the negative camp need deny the
existence of constraints on freedom that are located internally (see
Kramer 2003; Garnett 2007).</p>

<p>
To illustrate the independence of the two dimensions of type and
source, let us compare the case of Hayek, cited in the previous
subsection, with that of the unorthodox libertarian Hillel Steiner
(1974&ndash;5, 1994). On the one hand, Steiner has a much
<em>broader</em> view than Hayek of the possible <em>sources</em> of
constraints on freedom: he does not limit the set of such sources to
intentional actions of other persons, but extends it to cover all
actions of other agents, believing that any limitation of such social
sources can only be an arbitrary stipulation, usually arising from
some ideological bias. On the other hand, Steiner has an even
<em>narrower</em> view than Hayek about what <em>type</em> of obstacle
counts as a constraint on freedom: for Steiner, an agent counts as
unfree to do something only if it is <em>physically impossible</em>
for her to do that thing. Any extension of the constraint variable to
include other types of obstacle, such as the costs anticipated in
coercive threats, would, in his view, necessarily involve a reference
to the agent&rsquo;s desires, and we have seen (in sec. 2) that for
those liberals in the negative camp there is no conceptually necessary
relation between an agent&rsquo;s freedom and her desires. Consider
the coercive threat &lsquo;Your money or your life!&rsquo;. This does
not make it impossible for you to refuse to hand over your money, only
much less desirable for you to do so. If you decide not to hand over
the money, you will suffer the cost of being killed. That
<em>will</em> count as a restriction of your freedom, because it will
render physically impossible a great number of actions on your part.
But it is not the issuing of the threat that creates this unfreedom,
and you are not unfree until the sanction (described in the threat) is
carried out. For this reason, Steiner excludes threats&mdash;and with
them all other kinds of imposed costs&mdash;from the set of obstacles
that count as freedom-restricting. This conception of freedom derives
from Hobbes (<em>Leviathan</em>, chs. 14 and 21), and its defenders
often call it the <em>pure</em> negative conception (M. Taylor 1982;
Steiner 1994; Carter and Kramer 2008; cf. Flathman 1987) to
distinguish it from those <em>impure</em> negative conceptions that
make at least minimal references to the agent&rsquo;s beliefs, desires
or values (Oppenheim 1961, 1981; Benn and Weinstein 1971; Miller
1983).</p>

<p>
Steiner&rsquo;s account of the relation between freedom and coercive
threats might be thought to have counterintuitive implications. Many
laws that are normally thought to restrict negative freedom do not
physically prevent people from doing what is prohibited, but deter
them from doing so by threatening punishment. Are we to say, then,
that these laws do not restrict the negative freedom of those who obey
them? A solution to this problem may consist in saying that although a
law against doing some action, <em>x</em>, does not remove the freedom
to do <em>x</em>, it nevertheless renders physically impossible
certain <em>combinations</em> of actions that include doing <em>x</em>
and doing what would be precluded by the punishment. There is a
restriction of the person&rsquo;s <em>overall</em> negative
freedom&mdash;i.e. a reduction in the overall number of
act-combinations available to her&mdash;even though she does not lose
the freedom to do any specific thing considered in isolation (Carter
1999).</p>

<h2 id="ConcOverFree">7. The Concept of Overall Freedom</h2>

<p>
The concept of overall freedom appears to play an important role both
in everyday discourse and in contemporary political philosophy. We
commonly talk about people&rsquo;s freedom as <em>increasing</em> or
<em>decreasing</em>, we say that one society is <em>freer</em> than
another, and so on. Yet it is only over the last three decades that
philosophers have moved beyond the question of what it is to be free
to do or become this or that particular thing, in order to ask, in
addition, whether we can make sense of descriptive claims to the
effect that one person or society is freer than another, or of liberal
normative claims to the effect that freedom should be maximized or
that people should enjoy equal freedom or that they each have a right
to a certain minimum level of freedom. The literal meaningfulness of
such claims depends on the possibility of gauging degrees of overall
freedom, sometimes comparatively, sometimes absolutely.</p>

<p>
Theorists disagree, however, about the importance of the notion of
overall freedom. For some libertarian and liberal egalitarian
theorists, freedom is valuable as such. This suggests that more
freedom is better than less (at least <em>ceteris paribus</em>), and
that freedom is one of those goods that a liberal society ought to
distribute in a certain way among individuals. For other liberal
theorists, like Ronald Dworkin (1977, 2011) and the later Rawls
(1991), freedom is not valuable as such, and all claims about maximal
or equal freedom ought to be interpreted not as literal references to
a scalar good called &lsquo;liberty&rsquo; but as elliptical
references to the adequacy of this or that list of specific liberties,
or types of liberties, selected on the basis of values other than
liberty itself. Only the first group of theorists finds the notion of
overall freedom interesting.</p>

<p>
The theoretical problems involved in measuring overall freedom include
that of how an agent&rsquo;s available actions are to be individuated,
counted and weighted, and that of comparing and weighting different
constraint types (but not necessarily different constraint sources)
such as physical prevention, punishability, threats and manipulation).
How are we to make sense of the claim that the number of options
available to a person has increased? Should all options count for the
same in terms of degrees of freedom, or should they be weighted
according to their importance in terms of other values? If the latter,
does the notion of overall freedom really add anything of substance to
the idea that people should be granted those specific freedoms that
are valuable? Should the degree of variety among options also count?
And how are we to compare the unfreedom created by the physical
impossibility of an action with, say, the unfreedom created by the
difficulty or costliness or punishability of an action? It is only by
comparing these different kinds of actions and constraints that we
shall be in a position to compare individuals&rsquo; overall degrees
of freedom. These problems have been addressed, with differing degrees
of optimism, not only by mainstream political philosophers (Steiner
1983; Carter 1999; Kramer 2003; Garnett 2016; C&ocirc;t&eacute; 2020;
Carter and Steiner 2022) but also by theorists working at the
interface between philosophy and economics, including social choice
theorists interested in finding a freedom-based alternative to the
standard utilitarian or welfarist framework that has tended to
dominate their discipline (e.g. Pattanaik and Xu 1990, 1998; Hees
2000; Sen 2002; Sugden 1998, 2003, 2006; Bavetta 2004; Bavetta and
Navarra 2012, 2014). A particularly important line of research within
this social choice approach concerns the relevance of diversity of
available options for the measurement of freedom (See e.g. Hees 2004;
Sher 2021; Gravel et al. 2025; C&ocirc;t&eacute; 2025).</p>

<p>
MacCallum&rsquo;s framework is particularly well suited to the
clarification of such issues. For this reason, theorists working on
the measurement of freedom tend not to refer a great deal to the
distinction between positive and negative freedom. Most of them are
concerned with the notion of freedom understood as the availability of
options. This notion of freedom is unequivocally negative in
Berlin&rsquo;s sense at least where two conditions are met: first, the
source of unfreedom is limited to the actions of other agents, so that
natural or self-inflicted obstacles are not seen as decreasing an
agent&rsquo;s overall freedom; second, the actions one is free or
unfree to perform are weighted in some value-neutral way, so that one
is not seen as freer simply because the options available to one are
more valuable or conducive to one&rsquo;s self-realization. Of the
above-mentioned authors, only Steiner embraces both conditions
explicitly. Sen rejects both of them, despite not endorsing anything
like positive freedom in Berlin&rsquo;s sense. Many social choice
theorists seem to treat freedom as a dyadic relation, either assuming
that freedom is identical to ability or remaining agnostic about the
interpretation of MacCallum&rsquo;s constraint variable.</p>

<h2 id="DistStilUsef">8. Is the Distinction Still Useful?</h2>

<p>
We began with a simple distinction between two concepts of liberty,
and have progressed from this to the recognition that liberty might be
conceptualized in any number of ways, depending on how one interprets
the three variables of agent, constraints, and purposes. Negative
liberty is the absence of constraints, but so is positive liberty.
Positive liberty is the possibility of realizing certain ends, but so
is negative liberty. Despite the utility of MacCallum&rsquo;s triadic
formula and its strong influence on analytic philosophers, however,
Berlin&rsquo;s distinction has remained an important point of
reference in contemporary debates. Is this continued use of the
distinction philosophically well-founded? Let us consider some
possible reasons for this persistence, while also noting their
conceptual limits in light of the above discussion.</p>

<p>
A first reason for the persistence of the distinction might be thought
to lie in the difference between what Charles Taylor, in his defense
of positive liberty, called an <em>opportunity concept</em> and an
<em>exercise concept</em> of freedom (C. Taylor 1979). If one thinks
of freedom as an opportunity concept, then one is thinking of
<em>possibilities</em> open to an agent, what the agent <em>can</em>
do or, as Berlin put it, &lsquo;how many doors are open.&rsquo; If, by
contrast, one thinks of freedom as involving self-direction, which
implies the presence of control, one has in mind an exercise-concept
of freedom as opposed to an opportunity-concept. If freedom is an
exercise concept, it consists not merely in the <em>possibility</em>
of doing certain things, but in <em>actually doing</em> certain things
in certain ways&mdash;for example, in realizing one&rsquo;s true self
or in acting on the basis of rational and well-informed decisions.
MacCallum&rsquo;s single concept might be criticized as failing to
capture this exercise concept of freedom, for it seems to cover only
cases in which certain opportunities are open or closed for the
agent.</p>

<p>
However, this defense of the positive-negative distinction, as
coinciding with the distinction between exercise- and
opportunity-concepts of freedom, has been challenged by Eric Nelson
(2005). As Nelson points out, most of the theorists that are
traditionally located in the positive camp, such as Green or
Bosanquet, do not distinguish between freedom as the absence of
constraints and freedom as the doing or becoming of certain things.
For these theorists, freedom is the absence of any kind of constraint
whatsoever on the realization of one&rsquo;s true self (they adopt a
maximally extensive conception of constraints on freedom). The absence
of <em>all</em> factors that could prevent the action <em>x</em> is,
quite simply, equivalent to the realization of <em>x</em>. In other
words, if there really is <em>nothing</em> stopping me from doing
<em>x</em>&mdash;if I possess all the means to do <em>x</em>, and I
have a desire to do <em>x</em>, and no desire, irrational or
otherwise, not to do <em>x</em>&mdash;then I do <em>x</em>. If this
argument is correct, then MacCallum&rsquo;s triadic relation
accommodates the idea of freedom as an exercise concept.</p>

<p>
A second reason for the persistence of the distinction might be
thought to lie in the centrality of the relation between freedom and
ability. Many people seem to persist in the view that if freedom is
about being able to do things, then freedom should be understood as a
positive rather than a negative concept. Two limits of this view
should be evident from the above discussion. First, freedom as ability
fails to capture much of what Berlin had in mind in speaking of
positive liberty. Second, some conceptions that are classified as
negative by their proponents, such as Kramer&rsquo;s trivalent
conception (2003) or Garnett&rsquo;s bivalent ability-based conception
(2007; 2022a), identify freedom with ability. To these two limits can
be added a third: Christman&rsquo;s conception of liberty, which is
unequivocally positive, is in some respects ability-independent
(2025).</p>

<p>
A third reason might lie in the importance of the distinction between
morally-neutral conceptions and morally committed ones, where the
former are classed as negative and the latter as positive: for many
theorists in Berlin&rsquo;s negative camp, a person can be free to
perform an action whether it is good or evil, valuable or disvaluable,
permissible or impermissible, and they can be unfree to act
irrespective of whether the prevention in question is justified or
not. Most positive conceptions, by contrast, take the value or
permissibility of actions and/or restrictions to be relevant for
ascriptions of freedom and unfreedom. Here too, however, the proposed
method of categorization implies some false positives. Locke, normally
regarded as one of the fathers of classical liberalism and as a
proponent of negative freedom, states that to be at liberty is
&lsquo;to be free from restraint and violence from others.&rsquo; Yet
he also insists that liberty must not be confused with
&lsquo;licence&rsquo;, and &lsquo;that ill deserves the name of
confinement which hedges us in only from bogs and precipices&rsquo;
(<em>Second Treatise</em>, parags. 6 and 57). While Locke gives an
account of constraints on freedom that Berlin would call negative, he
seems to endorse an account of MacCallum&rsquo;s third variable (the
things one is free or unfree to do or become) that Berlin would call
positive, restricting it to actions that are not immoral (liberty is
not licence) and to those that are in the agent&rsquo;s own interests
(I am not unfree if prevented from falling into a bog). Many
contemporary liberals and libertarians have endorsed similarly
morally-laden definitions of freedom (Nozick 1974; Rothbard 1982;
Bader 2018).</p>

<p>
What these difficulties suggest is that the distinction between
negative and positive liberty does not correspond to a single clear
conceptual divide. But this is not to deny that the distinction
continues to have a meaning. Positive and negative conceptions are
best understood as stances taken up within intellectual traditions
that have developed historically in response to distinct philosophical
and political pressures (Garnett 2022b). In particular, the
distinction functions as a rough categorization of different ideas of
freedom in terms of the degree of critical distance implied between
their proponents and the classical liberal tradition. One way of
making sense of this degree of critical distance is by reference to
the theorist&rsquo;s degree of concern with the notion of the self.
Those on the positive side see questions about the nature and sources
of a person&rsquo;s beliefs, desires, and values as relevant to
questions about that person&rsquo;s freedom, whereas those on the
negative side, being more faithful to the classical liberal tradition,
tend to consider the raising of such questions as in some way
indicating a propensity to violate the agent&rsquo;s dignity or
integrity. One side takes a positive interest in the agent&rsquo;s
beliefs, desires, and values, while the other recommends that we avoid
doing so. This thought explains why the label &lsquo;pure negative
freedom&rsquo; is an uncontroversial one, even though political
philosophers diverge widely in how they assess the liberal normative
theories that build on its value. Pure negative conceptions completely
divorce questions about a person&rsquo;s freedom from questions about
their will. Impure negative conceptions make some assumptions about
typical or rational desires in order not to limit the relevant
constraint-types to physical impossibility. Positive conceptions go
further, problematizing the will of the agent as part of an endeavour
to construct freedom-based critical social and political theories.</p>
